WARNING LANGUAGE: Times Square at complete standstill. Protest for #TyreNichols

Migrant standoff. Single adult male asylum seekers are being moved from the Watson Hotel to the Brooklyn Cruise Terminal so migrant families with children can move in here. But advocates asked migrants not to board buses. Then a tent city popped up overnight. Activists say conditions at the terminal are inhumane. Eventually NYPD told migrants they can’t block the sidewalk, forcing them to break down tents. But there’s nothing illegal about standing around/sleeping in street. So dozens of migrants refusing to back down, as dozens of others are boarding the buses.

 “He could have easily, along with Governor Hochul opened up all the vacant luxury apartments! We are on 57th street right now. This Billionaires row! Half of the super towers on this street are empty!” - Sergio Tupac Uzurin, Activist

#AsylumSeekers who’ve made the move to the Brooklyn Cruise Terminal say the holdout #migrants are being “ridiculous.” They say they’re happy, comfortable, grateful for a warm place to sleep. cc @nycimmigrants @soniarincon

“I’d just like to say a big f*** you!” — first Board of Ed meeting at Bayville High School since 14-year-old Adriana Kuch took her life. Students and former students described decades of bullying. Say school administrators either ignored them, or were bullies themselves. Say they’ve been bullied by students, teachers, guidance counselors, even other parents.

Miss you so much @pierceworkshop it’s indescribable. You gave me hope in humanity; a constant reminder that people can be pure-hearted, good and noble. You and @shelleysellsnorthport are proof true love exists. You made me a better journalist, a better father, a better friend, a better human being. Thank you for sharing incredible memories with me. Thank you for taking this journey of life with me. I’m so fortunate to have been able to share just a few more laughs with you at the end. I’ll see you again my friend. Miss you brother. RIP Todd Pierce. (2nd pic celebrating the birth of my daughter in 2018. Then there’s Wawa, tasty cakes and hoagies minus the meat. Todd had this saying every time we sat down to eat he’d tell the waiter, “I know I don’t look like it but I’m a vegetarian.” But he wasn’t because of faith or health. In college he got a job at an aquarium. After that he couldn’t bring himself to eat anything that had “eyes or a tail or a mother.” That was Todd.)

Forever grateful that we got to share a few laughs until the very end my friend. I promise you and @shelleysellsnorthport that your daughter will grow up knowing what you meant to all of us, what you meant to journalism, what you meant to the world. 

Few memorable moments in this video montage: 

00:54 Todd taking the time to make these kids’ day in the Bronx. I captured him doing it again another day (at 01:29). That was the kind of heart he had. 

01:00 on a story about the L-pocalypse. Todd found the beauty in street music. I found in that moment Todd’s work to be the beauty worth capturing. 

01:23 this was taken in Koreatown. His daughter had just gotten into art and therefore into japanime etc. So I took him here and we joked that this pic was like a big foot sighting. Big hairy man in these teeny tiny aisles in Ktown. 

01:32 @alterpics captured this moment. While I was writing, Todd was killing gnats 😂.

01:50 Crashing for deadline with Jon Liles. Even in this moment of panic, with only minutes to spare and the piece not yet fed, Todd was calm and cool under pressure. 

01:56 Asian food (and at 2:02 Best Pizza in Brooklyn). Two foods this vegetarian could eat. And he loved to eat! Todd would always tell the waiter, “I know I don’t look like it but I’m a vegetarian!” But he wasn’t because of faith or health. In college he got a job at an aquarium. After that he couldn’t bring himself to eat anything that had “eyes or a tail or a mother.” That was Todd.
 
2:05 in a toy store doing a Christmas story. But I took this photo because like every story Todd was assigned, he was like a kid in a toy store. He got excited about every piece we did and put his all into everything. On this night, I captured Todd aka a kid in a toy store.

After every late night shift we’d work together @pierceworkshop would not only insist on dropping me off at my door but would never leave until I got through my lobby door. I’d tell him, “I’m a grown man. I can take care of myself. Stop being silly and hurry home to @shelleysellsnorthport the love of your life, she’s waiting for you.” And every night in the sincerest voice he’d say, “hey man thank you for a really good day. Seriously, thank you for a really really good day.” Todd, you made every day a really really good day. I hope all of your days now are really really good days. I was so lucky to have you in my life. This is the toughest loss in my life. RIP Todd Pierce.

@aafederation - Yesterday we were honored to be joined by @repgracemeng, US Ambassador to the UN Chris P. Lu for an important #AAPIHeritageMonth discussion on hard-fought successes in the past three years and ongoing gaps that still need to be addressed to make Asian American communities safer. 

Thank you @cefaan for moderating this insightful conversation with our panelists @aafenyc Chief of Staff My Trinh Chang, @nonviolentpeaceforce Director of Mutual Protection @kalamendoza, AAF Deputy Director Joo Han, and @stophatenyc Executive Director @hsnaveed on effective responses to anti-Asian hate that are rooted in empowering and investing in grassroots communities and organizations; ensuring our community members get the resources, mental health care, food, housing, education, and support they need; and building meaningful solidarity across communities so we all look out for each other.

The race for city council district 1 which includes Chinatown, Lower East Side, Wall St / Financial District. Interesting takeaways from last night’s forum. Every candidate is opposed to congestion pricing (even though district 1 constituents wouldn’t be charged the fee since they already live within the zone), only the incumbent says Rikers Island should be closed (but he is opposed to the proposed jail in Chinatown), they all give Mayor Adams a C on his handling of the migrant crisis, every candidate except for the Republican says it’s time to move away from outdoor dining sheds. Thank you @apavoicenewyork for having me moderate. #aapiheritagemonth

social_posts.post_text: Remember these faces. These are some of the courageous women who came forward against @columbia Univ. and former OBGYN Robert Hadden. See Us Rise: AAPI Resilience & Representation in Media is now officially available on Amazon. LINK BELOW!

INCREDIBLY HUMBLED by the foreword: 
“It is also a privilege to have CeFaan Kim in this book, leading off the interviews. I have always enjoyed his careful and thoughtful reporting on things that were happening in the New York City area. But what really made me take notice were the stories on the violence being inflicted on the AAPI community during the height of the pandemic. Day after day, week after week and month after month, he presented news stories of horrific acts of violence being committed against members of the AAPI community. He always reported with professionalism, composure, and grace, while people who looked like him were being subjected to the ugliness of society.”
 
www.amazon.com/See-Us-Rise-Resilience-Representation/dp/B0CKNGBFH1

Lastly a huge thank you to @abc7ny @marilugalvez @porshaabc7ny.
Thousands of Pro-Palestinian protestors marching over to the Israeli Consulate after demonstrating for hours in Times Square. They say resistance does not mean terrorism.
